---
import CalculatorLayout from '../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import SalaryCalculator from '../components/calculators/SalaryCalculator';
import { CALCULATOR_META } from '../data/calculator-meta';

const meta = CALCULATOR_META['take-home-pay'];
---

<CalculatorLayout {...meta}>
  <SalaryCalculator client:idle />

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <article class="mt-12 max-w-4xl prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert">

      <h2>What Is Take-Home Pay?</h2>
      <p>
        Take-home pay (also called net pay) is the amount of money that actually reaches your bank account after all mandatory deductions have been subtracted from your gross salary. In the UK, these deductions are handled automatically through the PAYE (Pay As You Earn) system run by HMRC. Your employer calculates and deducts income tax, National Insurance contributions, student loan repayments, and workplace pension contributions before paying you.
      </p>
      <p>
        The difference between your gross salary and your take-home pay can be substantial. On a £40,000 salary, for example, you lose over £8,500 to tax and NI alone, meaning roughly 21% of your earnings never reach your bank account. Understanding exactly where your money goes is the first step to managing your finances effectively and spotting opportunities to keep more of what you earn.
      </p>

      <h2>How We Calculate Your Take-Home Pay</h2>
      <p>
        This calculator applies the official HMRC rates for the 2026/27 tax year (6 April 2026 to 5 April 2027) in the same order your employer's payroll software does:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Start with your gross annual salary:</strong> the figure on your employment contract.</li>
        <li><strong>Determine your personal allowance:</strong> normally £12,570. If you earn over £100,000, your allowance is reduced by £1 for every £2 above the threshold, reaching zero at £125,140.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculate income tax:</strong> your taxable income (gross minus personal allowance) is split across the progressive tax bands. Only income within each band is taxed at that band's rate.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculate National Insurance:</strong> a separate deduction charged at 8% on earnings between £12,570 and £50,270, then 2% on earnings above £50,270.</li>
        <li><strong>Deduct student loan repayments</strong> (if applicable): 9% of earnings above your plan's threshold (6% for postgraduate loans).</li>
        <li><strong>Deduct pension contributions</strong> (if applicable): salary sacrifice reduces your gross pay before tax and NI; relief at source is deducted after tax.</li>
        <li><strong>The remainder is your take-home pay.</strong></li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Take-Home Pay Breakdown by Salary Level</h2>
      <p>
        Here is a detailed comparison of take-home pay at five common salary levels in England for 2026/27, assuming no student loan and no pension deductions:
      </p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Gross Salary</th>
            <th>Income Tax</th>
            <th>National Insurance</th>
            <th>Take-Home Pay</th>
            <th>Effective Rate</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>£20,000</td><td>£1,486</td><td>£594</td><td>£17,920</td><td>10.4%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>£30,000</td><td>£3,486</td><td>£1,394</td><td>£25,120</td><td>16.3%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>£40,000</td><td>£5,486</td><td>£2,194</td><td>£32,320</td><td>19.2%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>£50,000</td><td>£7,486</td><td>£2,994</td><td>£39,520</td><td>21.0%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>£60,000</td><td>£11,486</td><td>£3,194</td><td>£45,320</td><td>24.5%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>£80,000</td><td>£19,486</td><td>£3,594</td><td>£56,920</td><td>28.8%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>£100,000</td><td>£27,432</td><td>£4,010</td><td>£68,558</td><td>31.4%</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>
        Notice how the effective tax rate climbs as your salary increases. At £20,000 you keep nearly 90p of every pound. By £100,000, you keep less than 69p. The jump between £50,000 and £60,000 is particularly steep because the higher rate tax band (40%) kicks in at £50,270.
      </p>

      <h3>Worked Example: £35,000 Salary</h3>
      <p>
        Let's walk through a full take-home pay calculation for someone earning £35,000 in England with the standard 1257L tax code, no student loan, and no pension:
      </p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Gross annual salary</td><td class="text-right">£35,000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Personal allowance</td><td class="text-right">£12,570</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Taxable income</td><td class="text-right">£22,430</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>Income tax calculation:</strong></p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>£22,430 at 20% (basic rate)</td><td class="text-right">£4,486</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Total income tax</strong></td><td class="text-right"><strong>£4,486</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>National Insurance calculation:</strong></p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>£22,430 at 8% (£12,570 to £35,000)</td><td class="text-right">£1,794</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Total NI</strong></td><td class="text-right"><strong>£1,794</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>Take-home result:</strong></p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Gross salary</td><td class="text-right">£35,000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Income tax</td><td class="text-right">−£4,486</td></tr>
          <tr><td>National Insurance</td><td class="text-right">−£1,794</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Annual take-home pay</strong></td><td class="text-right"><strong>£28,720</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Monthly take-home</td><td class="text-right">£2,393</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Weekly take-home</td><td class="text-right">£552</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Effective tax rate</td><td class="text-right">17.9%</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Worked Example: £75,000 Salary</h3>
      <p>
        At £75,000, you cross into the higher rate band. Here's how the numbers work:
      </p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Gross annual salary</td><td class="text-right">£75,000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Personal allowance</td><td class="text-right">£12,570</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Taxable income</td><td class="text-right">£62,430</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>Income tax:</strong></p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>£37,700 at 20% (£12,570 to £50,270)</td><td class="text-right">£7,540</td></tr>
          <tr><td>£24,730 at 40% (£50,270 to £75,000)</td><td class="text-right">£9,892</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Total income tax</strong></td><td class="text-right"><strong>£17,432</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>National Insurance:</strong></p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>£37,700 at 8% (£12,570 to £50,270)</td><td class="text-right">£3,016</td></tr>
          <tr><td>£24,730 at 2% (£50,270 to £75,000)</td><td class="text-right">£495</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Total NI</strong></td><td class="text-right"><strong>£3,511</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>Take-home result:</strong></p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Gross salary</td><td class="text-right">£75,000</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Income tax</td><td class="text-right">−£17,432</td></tr>
          <tr><td>National Insurance</td><td class="text-right">−£3,511</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Annual take-home pay</strong></td><td class="text-right"><strong>£54,057</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Monthly take-home</td><td class="text-right">£4,505</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Effective tax rate</td><td class="text-right">27.9%</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>The £100,000 Trap: Personal Allowance Taper</h2>
      <p>
        One of the most misunderstood aspects of UK tax is what happens between £100,000 and £125,140. In this band, your personal allowance is gradually withdrawn: you lose £1 of allowance for every £2 you earn above £100,000. This means income in this range is effectively taxed at 60% (40% higher rate + 20% from the lost allowance).
      </p>
      <p>
        The result is counterintuitive: someone earning £125,140 takes home less additional money per pound than someone earning £200,000 (who pays 45% on additional income). If your salary falls in this range, increasing your pension contributions to bring your adjusted net income below £100,000 can save you thousands. Our <a href="/pension-contribution/">pension calculator</a> shows you the exact savings.
      </p>

      <h2>How Student Loans Affect Take-Home Pay</h2>
      <p>
        Student loan repayments are deducted from your salary alongside tax and NI. The repayment amount depends on which plan you're on:
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Plan</th><th>Threshold (2026/27)</th><th>Rate</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Plan 1</td><td>£26,900</td><td>9%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Plan 2</td><td>£29,385</td><td>9%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Plan 4 (Scotland)</td><td>£33,795</td><td>9%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Plan 5</td><td>£25,000</td><td>9%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Postgraduate Loan</td><td>£21,000</td><td>6%</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>
        For example, on a £35,000 salary with a Plan 2 loan, you'd repay 9% of the amount above £29,385, that's 9% × £5,615 = £505 per year, or about £42 per month. You can have multiple loans deducted simultaneously. Use our <a href="/student-loan/">student loan calculator</a> to see the combined effect.
      </p>

      <h2>Pension Contributions and Take-Home Pay</h2>
      <p>
        Since automatic enrolment was introduced, most UK employees contribute to a workplace pension. The method of contribution matters significantly for your take-home pay:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Salary sacrifice:</strong> Your gross pay is reduced before tax and NI are calculated. You save both income tax and National Insurance. A 5% pension contribution on a £40,000 salary via salary sacrifice costs you about £1,440 in lost take-home pay, but £2,000 goes into your pension.</li>
        <li><strong>Relief at source:</strong> Your contribution is taken from net pay, then the pension provider claims basic rate tax relief (20%) from HMRC. You save income tax but not NI. Higher rate taxpayers must claim additional relief through self-assessment.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Use our <a href="/pension-contribution/">pension contribution calculator</a> to compare both methods side by side and see exactly how much each costs you in take-home pay.
      </p>

      <h2>Take-Home Pay in Scotland vs England</h2>
      <p>
        If you live in Scotland, you pay Scottish income tax rates, which differ from the rest of the UK. Scotland has six income tax bands compared to three in England, Wales, and Northern Ireland. The key differences:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>A starter rate of 19% applies to the first £3,967 of taxable income (£12,570 to £16,537).</li>
        <li>The basic rate of 20% covers £16,537 to £29,526.</li>
        <li>An intermediate rate of 21% applies from £29,526 to £43,662.</li>
        <li>The higher rate is 42% (vs 40% in England) from £43,662 to £75,000.</li>
        <li>An advanced rate of 45% covers £75,000 to £125,140.</li>
        <li>The top rate is 48% (vs 45% in England) above £125,140.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        For most salaries under £30,000, the difference is minimal. Above £43,662, Scottish taxpayers pay noticeably more. On an £80,000 salary, a Scottish taxpayer pays roughly £1,500 more in income tax than someone in England on the same salary. Switch the region in the calculator above to see the precise difference for your salary.
      </p>

      <h2>Monthly vs Weekly Take-Home Pay</h2>
      <p>
        Most UK employees are paid monthly, receiving 1/12 of their annual take-home pay each month. However, some employers pay weekly (1/52 of annual) or four-weekly (every 4 weeks, giving 13 pay dates per year rather than 12). The calculator above lets you switch between yearly, monthly, weekly, daily, and hourly views.
      </p>
      <p>
        Be aware that if you're paid weekly, your monthly income will vary slightly depending on the number of weeks in each month. Some months have 4 paydays, while others have 5. Over the full year, the total is the same.
      </p>

      <h2>What If My Take-Home Pay Doesn't Match My Payslip?</h2>
      <p>
        If the take-home figure from this calculator doesn't match your actual payslip, there are several common explanations:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tax code differences:</strong> This calculator uses the standard 1257L code. If HMRC has adjusted your code (e.g., to collect underpaid tax from a previous year or to account for benefits in kind), your deductions will differ.</li>
        <li><strong>Benefits in kind:</strong> If you receive taxable benefits (company car, private medical insurance, etc.), their value may be deducted via your tax code.</li>
        <li><strong>Cumulative vs week 1/month 1:</strong> PAYE usually operates cumulatively, adjusting for previous months. At the start of the tax year or after a job change, your first payslips may differ.</li>
        <li><strong>Salary sacrifice schemes:</strong> Cycle-to-work, childcare vouchers, or other salary sacrifice arrangements reduce your gross pay before the calculator's starting point.</li>
        <li><strong>Payroll giving:</strong> Charitable donations via payroll are deducted before tax.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tips to Maximise Your Take-Home Pay</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Check your tax code annually.</strong> The standard code for 2026/27 is 1257L. If yours differs, check HMRC's explanation; incorrect codes are common after job changes.</li>
        <li><strong>Use salary sacrifice for pension contributions.</strong> You'll save on NI (8%) in addition to income tax. On a £50,000 salary with 5% contribution, salary sacrifice saves you roughly £200/year more than relief at source.</li>
        <li><strong>Claim Marriage Allowance.</strong> If your partner earns under £12,570, they can transfer £1,260 of their allowance to you, saving up to £252 per year.</li>
        <li><strong>Claim tax relief on work expenses.</strong> Flat-rate allowances for uniform washing (£60/year), professional subscriptions, and working from home (£6/week) can add up.</li>
        <li><strong>Consider timing around the £100,000 threshold.</strong> If you're near £100,000, increasing pension contributions to stay below can save you £5,028 in lost personal allowance.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Take-Home Pay vs Salary Calculator: What's the Difference?</h2>
      <p>
        Our <a href="/">salary calculator</a> provides a quick overview of your net pay. This take-home pay calculator does the same calculation but is optimised for people who want to understand the full breakdown, seeing exactly how much goes to income tax, NI, student loans, and pension at each level. If you need the reverse calculation (what gross salary do I need for a target take-home amount?), use our <a href="/required-salary/">required salary calculator</a>.
      </p>

